25 May 2012 20:14






The classification in this case is based mainly on the fact that it's a giant living face on the side of a well-known geological landmark, that its existence is attested to in folklore dating back centuries, and that there's fundamentally nothing to stop someone from wandering up and having a chat with it. On top of that, we don't really understand why or how it exists, or whether it's just a face on a cliff or there's more of it buried underground, and we can't do much to find out because we risk destroying it altogether.





